HTML SVG
HTML SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) is used to create vector graphics that can be scaled up or down without losing any quality. SVG is an XML-based language that allows you to create graphics, logos, and icons.

Basic Usage
To use SVG in HTML, you can use the svg element.


<svg width="100" height="100">
  <circle cx="50" cy="50" r="40" fill="red" />
</svg>


SVG Elements
1. circle: Used to create a circle.
2. rect: Used to create a rectangle.
3. line: Used to create a line.
4. text: Used to create text.

Attributes
1. width and height: Specify the width and height of the SVG element.
2. fill: Specifies the fill color of the SVG element.
3. stroke: Specifies the stroke color of the SVG element.
4. stroke-width: Specifies the stroke width of the SVG element.

Real-time Examples
1. Creating a circle: You can use the circle element to create a circle.

<svg width="100" height="100">
  <circle cx="50" cy="50" r="40" fill="red" />
</svg>


2. Creating a rectangle: You can use the rect element to create a rectangle.

<svg width="100" height="100">
  <rect x="10" y="10" width="80" height="80" fill="blue" />
</svg>


3. Creating text: You can use the text element to create text.

<svg width="200" height="100">
  <text x="10" y="50" font-size="24" fill="black">Hello, World!</text>
</svg>


CSS Styling
You can style SVG elements using CSS.


svg {
  border: 1px solid black;
}

circle {
  fill: green;
}


Questions and Answers
1. Q: What is SVG?
    - A: SVG stands for Scalable Vector Graphics, which is used to create vector graphics that can be scaled up or down without losing any quality.

2. Q: How do you create a circle in SVG?
    - A: You can use the circle element to create a circle in SVG.

3. Q: Can you style SVG elements using CSS?
    - A: Yes, you can style SVG elements using CSS.

4. Q: What are the benefits of using SVG?
    - A: SVG allows you to create scalable graphics that can be used in a variety of contexts, including logos, icons, and graphics.

Full Example:


<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>HTML SVG</title>
  <style>
    svg {
      border: 1px solid black;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <svg width="100" height="100">
    <circle cx="50" cy="50" r="40" fill="red" />
  </svg>
  <svg width="100" height="100">
    <rect x="10" y="10" width="80" height="80" fill="blue" />
  </svg>
  <svg width="200" height="100">
    <text x="10" y="50" font-size="24" fill="black">Hello, World!</text>
  </svg>
</body>
</html>
